 result of this rollback and waves of severe financial crises soon follow. As Lee deftly shows, the Long Depression of 1873–1896, the Great Depression of 1929–1939, and the financial crisis of 2008 are part of the same recurrent pattern: global competition disrupts the longstanding political equilibria, prompting a search for new, risky ideas among the most powerful states. From Malaise to Meltdown presents a sweeping but accessible historical narrative about the coevolution of power, ideas, and domestic politics, supported by archival research into the risky decisions that ushered in the worst financial crises in history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDeregulationxHistory. 0aFinancial crisesxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aeconomic decline.  aeconomic history.  afinancial crises.  afinancial history.  afinancial.  aglobalization.  ainternational competition.  amonetary relations.  aregulation.  arivalry.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753510040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487535100423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487535100.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles